@c ================================================================================
@node Iterate
@section Iterate

Iterate support is provided by a separate ASDF system, FSet/Iterate, so as not to pull in Iterate as
a dependency if you're not using it.  To load it, do @code{(ql:quickload "fset/iterate")}.

There are two symbol collisions between packages @code{fset/iterate} and @code{iterate} that you
will need to deal with.  One is relatively straightforward: @code{fset/iterate} exports a different
version of @code{unioning}; see the description below.

The other has to do with the symbol @code{with}.  Astonishingly, though both FSet and Iterate export
a symbol @code{with}, they do not conflict in practice.  Iterate doesn't fdefine @code{with}, but
uses it as a clause head, part of its syntax.  Since it would never make sense to call
@code{fset:with} without doing something with its return value, an @code{fset:with} call will never
appear at top level within the body of an @code{iter} form, so @code{iter} could never mistake it
for a clause head.  That means you actually can write something like this:

@example
    (iter ... (with foo = (with some-set new-element)) ... )
@end example

although, to keep your fellow developers' heads from exploding, you might be better advised to
package-qualify the two occurrences of @code{with}.

[But see @uref{https://gitlab.common-lisp.net/iterate/iterate/-/issues/27, this Iterate issue}.  As
of this writing, reloading Iterate could make this stop working; also, that page has an Iterate
patch you might need for it to work in all cases.]

With that in mind, I recommend adding the following to any packages in which you want to use FSet's
Iterate support:

@example
  (:shadowing-import-from :fset2 #:with)
  (:shadowing-import-from :fset/iterate #:unioning)
@end example

Here are the clauses and accumulators defined by FSet/Iterate:

@deffn {Iterate clause} {for @var{var} in-set @var{set}}
Yields the elements of @var{set}.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate clause} {for @var{var} in-bag @var{bag}}
Yields the elements of @var{bag}.  Elements with multiplicities greater than 1 will be repeated that
many times.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate clause} {for (@var{var} @var{count}) in-bag @var{bag}}
Yields the pairs of @var{bag}, binding @var{var} to each element and @var{count} to its
multiplicity.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate clause} {for (@var{key} @var{value}) in-map @var{map}}
Yields the pairs of @var{map}, binding @var{key} to each key and @var{value} to its value.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate clause} {for @var{var} in-seq @var{seq}} @ @r{&optional} @r{from} from @r{upfrom} upfrom @
        @r{downfrom} downfrom @r{to} to @r{downto} downto @r{above} above @r{below} below @
        @r{by} step @r{with-index} with-index
Yields the elements of @var{seq}.  The index range can be specified with @var{from}/@var{uptrom} or
@var{downfrom}, and/or @var{to}, @var{downto}, @var{above}, or @var{below}.  @var{step}, if
supplied, gives the index step.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate clause} {for @var{var} in-collection @var{coll}}
Yields the elements of @var{coll}, which can be any collection which has an @code{iterator} method
conforming to the FSet @href{Stateful Iterators, stateful iterator protocol}.
@end deffn

FSet's Iterate support also includes several accumulators for constructing new collections:

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {collect-set @var{expr}} @ @r{&optional initial-value} init-val @r{into} var-spec
Collects values into a set.  By default, this is a @code{ch-set} organized by @code{compare}; supply
@var{init-val} to construct a different kind of set.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {collect-bag @var{expr}} @ @r{&optional initial-value} init-val @r{into} var-spec
Collects values into a bag.  By default, this is a @code{ch-bag} organized by @code{compare}; supply
@var{init-val} to construct a different kind of bag.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {collect-bag @var{expr} count @var{count-expr}} @ @r{&optional initial-value} init-val @r{into} var-spec
Collects value/count pairs into a bag; that is, on each execution, adds @var{count-expr} instances
of @var{expr} to the bag.  By default, this is a @code{ch-bag} organized by @code{compare}; supply
@var{init-val} to construct a different kind of bag.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {collect-seq @var{expr}} @ @r{&optional into} var-spec
Collects values into a seq.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {collect-map (@var{key} @var{value})} @ @r{&optional initial-value} init-val @r{into} var-spec
Collects key/value pairs into a map.  By default, this is a @code{ch-map} organized by
@code{compare}; supply @var{init-val} to construct a different kind of map.  If a key is supplied
more than once, the @emph{last} value supplied for it is retained.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {collect-map-to-sets (@var{key} @var{value})} @ @r{&optional initial-value} init-val @r{into} var-spec
Collects key/value pairs into a map, collecting the values supplied for each key into a set; that
is, the result is a map whose range values are sets.  By default, the map is a @code{ch-map}
organized by @code{compare}, and the sets are @code{ch-set}s organized by @code{compare}; supply
@var{init-val} to construct a different kind of map (the map's default must be a set).
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {unioning @var{expr}} @ @r{&optional initial-value} init-val @r{into} var-spec
Unions sets into a result set.  If @var{init-val} is provided, the result will be of the same type
and organization; otherwise, it will be of the same type and organization as the first set received,
unless the iteration terminates without executing this clause at all, in which case the result will
be the empty @code{ch-set}.

(My recommendation is for @code{fset/iterate:unioning} to shadow @code{iter:unioning} as described
above; but it's up to you whether to accept it.  Since you're using FSet, you probably want to avoid
unioning lists, which takes quadratic time.  However, FSet's version doesn't support the @code{at}
keyword, nor does it normally offer the ordering guarantee that @code{iter:unioning} does, although
you can get that effect by supplying @code{initial-value (replay-set)} and binding @code{expr} to
replay sets.)
@end deffn
@c Mention bags?  The doc string does, but this operation on bags doesn't seem that likely to be
@c useful.  @code{bag-summing} would be likelier; I guess I should write it.

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {intersecting @var{expr}} @ @r{&optional initial-value} init-val @r{into} var-spec
Intersects sets into a result set.  If @var{init-val} is provided, the result will be of the same
type and organization; otherwise, it will be of the same type and organization as the first set
received, unless the iteration terminates without executing this clause at all, in which case the
result will be the @href{Function full-set, full set} built on @code{ch-set}.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {concating @var{expr}} @ @r{&optional into} var-spec
Concatenates successive seqs into a result seq.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {map-unioning @var{expr}} @ @r{&optional combining-with} val-fn @r{initial-value} init-val @r{into} var-spec
Map-unions maps into a result map (@pxref{Method map-union (map map)}).  If @var{val-fn} is
provided, it is used to combine values corresponding to the same key; the default is to overwrite
the value from the earlier map with the later value.  If @var{init-val} is provided, the result will
be of the same type and organization; otherwise, it will be of the same type and organization as the
first set received, unless the iteration terminates without executing this clause at all, in which
case the result will be the empty @code{ch-map}.
@end deffn

@deffn {Iterate accumulator} {map-intersecting @var{expr}} @ @r{&optional combining-with} val-fn @r{into} var-spec
Map-intersects maps into a result map (@pxref{Method map-intersection (map map)}).  If @var{val-fn}
is provided, it is used to combine values corresponding to the same key; the default is to overwrite
the value from the earlier map with the later value.  The result will be of the same type and
organization as the first set received, unless the iteration terminates without executing this
clause at all, in which case the result will be @code{nil}.

[Discussion: in the case of intersecting zero maps, there's nothing reasonable this could return,
since there's no such thing as a ``full map''.  (There is a full binary relation, but it's not a
function.)  So it may as well just return @code{nil}.  For the same reason, there's no point in it
accepting an initial value; if you want to change organizations, just @code{convert} the result.]
@end deffn
